        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the CO(2-1) line at 230 GHz in band 6 in configuration C34-7, with a single pointing since the targeted eastern component of SBS0335-052 (~5'') falls well within the ALMA field-of-view. 

Imaging requirements: 
From IR/radio observations, we know that the emission from the cold material is compact (&lt;0.1''). We choose a 0.2'' (60 pc) spatial resolution. This is one of the most extended configuration in band 6, but is required to minimize beam dilution effects and ensure a detection of CO, optimizing the signal-to-noise. Although we will not resolve individual molecular clumps (~3 pc), a finer resolution than 0.2'' is very challenging since we have no information on the spatial distribution of CO in this galaxy. No extended emission will be missed. 

Correlator setup: 
We select dual polarization and 4 spectral windows: 1 on the CO(2-1) line and the others at different frequencies to probe the continuum in the band. The continuum information will be used to further constrain our SED models. The expected line width is about 50 km/s and we aim for velocity resolution of 5 km/s, thus a bandwidth of 1875 MHz with element resolution of 976 kHz (1.3 km/s) is sufficient. 

Sensitivity requirements: 
We estimate the CO(2-1) sensitivity by converting its SFR surface density to a molecular surface density and then using a metallicity-scaled Xco factor (details in the science justification). The estimated peak flux density is 2.3 mJy, and the requested rms, for a 5-sigma detection, is 0.46 mJy. This corresponds to a 2.5 h integration time (or 5.2 h total ALMA time). </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
